The paper deals with graph problems related to interval graphs, which are a fundamental topic in computer science and discrete mathematics. The use of interval graphs in molecular biology and genomic research suggests a connection to computational biology (cs.CB), but the focus of the paper is on algorithmic and combinatorial aspects, which are more closely related to sub-categories such as data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), graph theory (cs.GT), and computational complexity (cs.CC). Among these, cs.DS and cs.CG are the most likely sub-categories, as they deal with the design and analysis of efficient algorithms for geometric and combinatorial problems, which are relevant to the kernelization results presented in the paper.
